english:
  title: 'A Eulogy for the Name of Lee, Inscribed on the Royal Edict: With Preface'
  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I served King Gongin alongside Yi Kong of Seo-won. While he stood guard at the palace and I held the brush for royal documents, though our paths were different—one martial, one civil—we walked together morning and night as brothers in spirit. Moreover, I was connected to his family by marriage through the Hans, and so our affection ran deep.

    At that time, his father, Master Uigok, still enjoyed good health. The King, seeing in him a scholar of great age and virtue, showed him special respect. He personally wrote four characters—"Uigok Cheong-gyeong"—and bestowed them upon him. The Prime Minister Mok-eun composed a eulogy for this. To the son, he wrote the characters "Seung-do," his name. Originally written as "do" meaning measure, the King changed it to "do" meaning to cross by boat, embedding deeper significance. The hopes invested were not slight.

    Before long, the King passed from this world, and Yi Kong soon followed. Alas, what loss! His son, the Junior Official Joong-gi, came bearing these words: "My grandfather and father both received the royal hand-written edict. For my grandfather, it expressed the King's respect, hence a courtesy name. For my father, it expressed his love, hence his given name. My grandfather already received Master Mok-eun's eulogy, yet no one has composed one for my father's name. How will posterity know it came from the royal brush? You, having known my father, would you compose this for us?"

    The refined brushwork of King Gongin and the noble lineage of the Lee family—these Master Mok-eun has already fully praised, and I dare not add to his words. Yet knowing this family through three generations, I find that thirty years have somehow passed between one moment and the next. Remembering those days, my heart dwells eternally between the living and the departed. Viewing this edict, I cannot suppress a profound sorrow.

    Therefore I have composed this eulogy:

    Behold—the brilliant Milky Way inscribes its image upon heaven,
    And its radiance descends to illumine all things below.
    Looking up at those characters like gold,
    They are treasures passed down through time.

    Who receives such singular grace?
    Only the virtuous minister deserves it.
    The crossing by boat—his name—
    The hopes embedded were never slight.

    Because such substance endured,
    So too the name remains.
    The name persists though events have passed,
    And sorrow settles in the heart.

    Let his descendants guard it well,
    And preserve his honored name forever.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'King Gongin (恭愍王): Ruled Goryeo during a turbulent period of the late 14th century. He was known for his erratic behavior and was eventually deposed.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Master Mok-eun (牧隱): Yi Saek, a prominent Confucian scholar and statesman who served multiple Goryeo kings. He was renowned for his literary talents and virtue.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'The name ''Seung-do'' (承渡): The substitution of ''do'' (度/渡) carries symbolic weight—it transforms from a character meaning ''measure'' or ''standard'' into one meaning ''to cross by boat,'' suggesting the bearer will traverse difficulties with grace.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Thirty years (三紀): A traditional measurement of time; one ''ji'' equals ten years in this context.'
